Do we need to think about what we want to do if we don't want to do it?
Related stories to [2019-09-11 Motivation System Improvement Proposal].
	It's [productive] to do what you [want to do].
	There are people [who] don't know what they want to do.
	He believed that people who don't know what they want to do need to figure out for themselves what they want to do.
		But isn't this idea incorrect?
	In other words, if the computer can suggest "what you want to do" to such people and motivate them to do it, it's good!
	If you leave that person alone, he/she will waste time without finding what he/she wants to do, so there is no particular loss even if the computer-suggested "what he/she wants to do" is wrong.
